    <note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p
        xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Hamilton became the publisher of the <title
          xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Critical Review</title> in 1758 and took over the
        journal's editorship from Tobias Smollett in 1763. He was friendly with David Garrick,
        Samuel Johnson, and Oliver Goldsmith.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Although
        there are three Archibald Hamiltons, all of whom were printers, grandfather (d. 9 March
        1793), father (who predeceases him, 6 October 1792) and two son (dates unknown: Archibald
        and Samuel), the identification can be ascertained by the entry of 28 Aug 1791 when Godwin
        notes his age being 71 - corresponding with the <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
          >DNB</title>.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Hamilton appears with <persName
          xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="ROB01">Robinson</persName>, <persName
          xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="HOL01">Holcroft</persName> and <persName
          xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="NIC01">Nicholson</persName> but as the diary goes
        on the meetings seem to become less intimate and more related to business (letters and calls
        instead of dinners). For entries after Archibald Hamilton's death see <persName
          xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="HAM03">Samuel Hamilton</persName>.</p></note>
